Consider the right angle triangle in the truss problem as shown above, where $$\small\theta$$ =  53o and $$\small\phi$$ =  37o, and the force applied on the truss system is  142N (indicated by the red arrow).

Use the convention that upward forces (vertical), forces to the right (horizontal), and anti-clockwise moments are positive, when answering this question.

Giving your answers to the nearest whole number, calculate:

A)

The reaction forces.

RA_x: {1:NUMERICAL:=0:0#Good job!!~*#Incorrect}N

RA_y: {1:NUMERICAL:=91:2.2643#Good job!!~*#Incorrect}N

RC: {1:NUMERICAL:=51:1.2857#Good job!!~*#Incorrect}N

B)

The internal forces on each member.

FAB: {1:NUMERICAL:=-113:-2.8352#Good job!!~*#Incorrect}N

FAC: {1:NUMERICAL:=68:1.7062#Good job!!~*#Incorrect}N

FBC: {1:NUMERICAL:=-85:-2.1364#Good job!!~*#Incorrect}N

C)

Indicate if each member is tension or compression from the options below.

FAB

{1:MCV:~Tension#Incorrect~=Compression#Good Job!}

FAC

{1:MCV:~Compression#Incorrect~=Tension#Good job!}

FBC

{1:MCV:~=Compression#Good Job!~Tension#Incorrect}

generalfeedback.text:
Use the diagram above to help solve this problem.

Consider the whole truss as a single beam.

Find the reaction forces by taking moments about A or C.

Consider each joint seperately to find the forces on each member and assume all members are in tension (i.e. draw them in tension on your force diagram).

Find a joint where only one or two forces are unknown and repeat until all the forces are found.

Finally, a positive force means the element is in tension, otherwise it is in compression.


Here is the full worked solution for this question:

PART A

RA_x must equal zero, as there are no other horizontal forces to consider, and the system is in equilibirum.

Using simple trigonometry, the distance AD = (h/tan$$\small\theta$$), and the distance DC = (h/tan$$\small\phi$$).

By taking moments about A, we can derive the following expression:

(RC x (AD + DC)) - (F x AD) = 0

We can then substitute in the distances AD and DC (as calculated above), the values of F, $$\small\theta$$ and $$\small\phi$$ as given in the question, and divide the whole expression by h.

This gives a value of RC =  51N.

For the whole system to be in equilibrium: RA_y + RC - F = 0.

Therefore: RA_y =  91N.

PARTS B & C

Starting with joint A, and by looking at vertical forces, we can derive the following expression:

RA_y + (FAB x sin$$\small\theta$$) = 0

Therefore: FAB =  -113N.

The  negative sign here indicates that this member is in  compression.

Looking at horizontal forces at joint A, we can derive the following expression:

RA_x + (FAB x cos$$\small\theta$$) + FAC = 0

Therefore: FAC =  68N.

The  positive sign here indicates that this member is in  tension.

Next, looking at horizontal forces at joint B, we can derive the following expression:

(FBC x sin$$\small\theta$$) - (FAB x sin$$\small\phi$$) = 0

Therefore: FBC =  -85N.

The  negative sign here indicates that this member is in  compression.

You can then calculate the vertical forces at joint B, and both the horizontal and vertical forces at joint C, as a final check.

hint.text:
HINT

Remember for a system to be in equlibirium the following conditions must be satisfied:

$$\small\sum$$ Mz=0

$$\small\sum$$ Fy=0

$$\small\sum$$ Fx=0

You may find it helpful to treat the whole truss as a single beam initially in order to find the reaction forces.

You can then draw a force diagram for each joint, and use the method of joints to calculate all of the remaining forces.

To answer this question, set up internal forces by assuming that each member is in tension, a negative value would therefore indicate that a member is in compression.

Remember to indicate if a force has a positive or negative value in your answers, where appropriate.

Use the diagram above to help solve this problem.

Consider the whole truss as a single beam.

Find the reaction forces by taking moments about A or C.

Consider each joint seperately to find the forces on each member and assume all members are in tension (i.e. draw them in tension on your force diagram).

Find a joint where only one or two forces are unknown and repeat until all the forces are found.

Finally, a positive force means the element is in tension, otherwise it is in compression.


Here is the full worked solution for this question:

PART A

RA_x must equal zero, as there are no other horizontal forces to consider, and the system is in equilibirum.

Using simple trigonometry, the distance AD = (h/tan$$\small\theta$$), and the distance DC = (h/tan$$\small\phi$$).

By taking moments about A, we can derive the following expression:

(RC x (AD + DC)) - (F x AD) = 0

We can then substitute in the distances AD and DC (as calculated above), the values of F, $$\small\theta$$ and $$\small\phi$$ as given in the question, and divide the whole expression by h.

This gives a value of RC =  54N.

For the whole system to be in equilibrium: RA_y + RC - F = 0.

Therefore: RA_y =  26N.

PARTS B & C

Starting with joint A, and by looking at vertical forces, we can derive the following expression:

RA_y + (FAB x sin$$\small\theta$$) = 0

Therefore: FAB =  -46N.

The  negative sign here indicates that this member is in  compression.

Looking at horizontal forces at joint A, we can derive the following expression:

RA_x + (FAB x cos$$\small\theta$$) + FAC = 0

Therefore: FAC =  38N.

The  positive sign here indicates that this member is in  tension.

Next, looking at horizontal forces at joint B, we can derive the following expression:

(FBC x sin$$\small\theta$$) - (FAB x sin$$\small\phi$$) = 0

Therefore: FBC =  -66N.

The  negative sign here indicates that this member is in  compression.

You can then calculate the vertical forces at joint B, and both the horizontal and vertical forces at joint C, as a final check.
